{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181022142239|865214965","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Joe_Barton","to":"Joe Barton"}],"pages":{"938613":{"pageid":938613,"ns":0,"title":"Joe Barton","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-22T14:22:45Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Other people||Joseph Barton (disambiguation){{!}}Joseph Barton}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Joe Barton\n|image        = Joe Barton official congressional photo.jpg\n|office       = Chair of the [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|House Energy Committee]]\n|term_start   = February 16, 2004\n|term_end     = January 3, 2007\n|predecessor  = [[Billy Tauzin]]\n|successor    = [[John Dingell]]\n|state1       = [[Texas]]\n|district1    = {{ushr|TX|6|6th}}\n|term_start1  = January 3, 1985\n|term_end1    = \n|predecessor1 = [[Phil Gramm]]\n|successor1   = \n|birth_name   = Joe Linus Barton\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1949|9|15}}\n|birth_place  = [[Waco, Texas|Waco]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Janet Winslow|1971|1992|end=div.}}<br>{{marriage|Terri Brasier|2004|2015|end=div.}}\n|children     = 4\n|education    = [[Texas A&M University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Purdue University]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])\n}}\n'''Joe Linus Barton''' (born September 15, 1949) is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] politician representing {{ushr|Texas|6|}} ([[:File:TX06 109.gif|map]]) in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] since 1985, and a member of the [[Tea Party Caucus]]. The district includes [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]], part of [[Fort Worth]], and several small towns and rural areas south of the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Metroplex]]. In 2014, Barton became the longest-serving member of the Texas congressional delegation.<ref>[http://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/Focus-of-sexting-scandal-won-t-run-for-12396500.php \"Barton, facing sexting scandal, won\u2019t run for re-election to Congress,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''San Antonio Express-News''.</ref>\n\nBarton describes himself as \"a constant defender of conservative ideals and values\".<ref name=autogenerated15>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/article57787228.html \"Battle for Texas\u2019 6th Congressional District,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref> He advocates for deregulation of the electricity and [[natural gas]] industries,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://joebarton.house.gov/biography/|title=Biography {{!}} U.S. Representative Joe Barton|website=joebarton.house.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-09-25}}</ref> and serves as vice-chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://energycommerce.house.gov/meet-vice-chairman/|title=Meet the Vice Chairman \u2013 Energy and Commerce Committee|work=Energy and Commerce Committee|access-date=2017-09-25|language=en-US}}</ref> He is skeptical that manmade [[carbon emissions]] have contributed to [[global warming]],<ref name=twsRStone101>Andy Kroll, November 3, 2016, ''Rolling Stone'', [https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/features/why-republicans-still-reject-the-science-of-global-warming-w448023 Why Republicans Still Reject the Science of Global Warming], Retrieved May 21, 2017, \"modern-day Republican Party, protecting fossil fuels ... was a religion ... didn't have a chance in hell of persuading someone like Barton to join his cause.... open hostility to science and evidence and facts...</ref><ref name=twsPolFact994>Louis Jacobson, January 15, 2015, PolitFact, [http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2015/jan/15/facebook-posts/widely-shared-meme-oversimplifies-joe-bartons-2009/ Widely shared meme oversimplifies Joe Barton's 2009 comment on wind energy, climate change], Retrieved May 21, 2017</ref> is a proponent of the use of [[fossil fuel]]s,<ref name=twsTimemag191>Jay Newton-Small and Katy Steinmetz, June 18, 2010, ''TIME'', [http://content.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1997963,00.html Eight More Deep Thoughts from Rep. Joe Barton], Retrieved May 22, 2017, \"in the mid-1980s, Barton took a hard Texan line against spies ... he said all spies should be given the death penalty as \"retribution\" to fellow citizens... \"We wouldn't go through the legalities that we have to because of our due process.\"</ref> voted in favor of the May 2017 GOP plan to replace Obamacare,<ref name=twsWashPost848>Kim Soffen, Darla Cameron, Kevin Uhrmacher, May 4, 2017, ''Washington Post'', [https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/ahca-house-vote/ How the House voted to pass the GOP health-care bill], Retrieved May 22, 2017</ref> supports President [[Donald Trump]]'s ban on immigration from certain predominantly Muslim nations,<ref name=\"Blake1\"/><ref name=texastrib101>ABBY LIVINGSTON AND BOBBY BLANCHARD, January 29, 2017, ''Texas Tribune'', [https://www.texastribune.org/2017/01/29/texas-congressional-support-trump-refugee-ban-fall/ Texas congressional delegation largely silent on Trump travel ban], Retrieved May 21, 2017, \"Barton ... backed the ban...\"</ref> and supports the death penalty for persons caught spying.<ref name=twsTimemag191/> Barton led a successful effort to repeal the oil export ban in the House in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bna.com/skeptics-won-oil-n57982065740/|title=Skeptics Won Over for Oil Export Win, Barton Says|website=www.bna.com|access-date=2017-09-25}}</ref> His environmental record of defending industries against tighter pollution controls earned him the nickname \"Smokey Joe.\"<ref name=autogenerated7>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article186068468.html \"Nude photo posted online of U.S. Rep. Joe Barton,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref>\n\nBarton came to national prominence after telling a citizen at a town hall meeting to \"shut up.\"<ref name=twsWashPost101>Lindsay Bever, March 15, 2017, ''Washington Post'', [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/03/15/you-sir-shut-up-republican-congressman-shouts-down-a-constituent-at-tense-town-hall/?wpisrc=nl_evening&wpmm=1 \u2018You, sir, shut up!\u2019: Republican congressman shouts down a constituent at tense town hall], Retrieved March 15, 2017, \"\"You, sir, shut up.\"... The crowd responded with a combination of apparent anger and applause, with one attendee screaming: \"What is that? You don't tell anybody to shut up! You work for us!\"\"</ref> He came to national attention again when nude selfie photos of him \u2013 taken from video he had taken of himself [[masturbating]], that he had shared with women \u2013 surfaced online in 2017, along with messages with sexual overtones that he had sent to a female constituent while he was married.<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/11/22/republican-rep-joe-barton-apologizes-after-lewd-photo-text-surfaces.html \"Republican Rep. Joe Barton apologizes after lewd photo surfaces,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] Fox News.</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>[https://www.politico.com/story/2017/11/22/gop-congressman-barton-apologizes-for-nude-selfie-259442 \"GOP congressman Barton apologizes for nude selfie\" \u2013 POLITICO<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.dallasnews.com/opinion/editorials/2017/11/27/cringe-worthy-photo-let-voters-decide-rep-joe-bartons-future \"After cringe-worthy photo, let voters decide on Rep. \"Joe Barton's future\" | Editorials,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Dallas News''.</ref> In November 2017, Barton announced that he will retire from [[United States Congress|Congress]] at the end of his current term, and will not seek re-election in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Texas, 2018|2018]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leslie |first=Katie |date=November 30, 2017 |title= Rep. Joe Barton: I will not seek re-election|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2017/11/30/rep-joe-barton-will-not-seek-re-election |work=[[Dallas Morning News]] |location=Dallas, TX |access-date=November 30, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nBarton was born in [[Waco, Texas|Waco]], [[Texas]], the son of Bess Wynell (n\u00e9e Buice) and Larry Linus Barton.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com/~battle/reps/barton.htm |title=Joe Barton Genealogy |publisher=Freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.com |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010150518/http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/barton.htm |archivedate=2012-10-10 |deadurl=no}}</ref> He graduated from [[Waco High School]]. He attended [[Texas A&M University]] in [[College Station, Texas|College Station]] on a Gifford-Hill Opportunity Award scholarship, and received a [[bachelor's degree|B.S.]] in [[industrial engineering]] in 1972.<ref>{{cite web\n  | title =Proceedings\n  | publisher =Texas A&M University\n  | date =2004-04-06\n  | url =http://cheweb.tamu.edu/tiact/proceedings2004.pdf\n  | accessdate =2009-05-13 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060904114703/http://cheweb.tamu.edu/tiact/proceedings2004.pdf |archivedate = 2006-09-04}}</ref> An [[Master of Science|M.Sc.]] in industrial administration from [[Purdue University]] followed in 1973.\n\nFollowing college, Barton entered private industry until 1981, when he became a [[White House Fellow]] and served under [[United States Secretary of Energy]] [[James Burrows Edwards|James B. Edwards]]. Later, he began consulting for [[Atlantic Richfield]] Oil and Gas Co., before being elected to the [[United States Congress]] in 1984.<ref name=HouseBio>{{cite web |url=http://joebarton.house.gov/biography1/ |title=Joe Barton Congressman \u2013 6th District of Texas |publisher=Joebarton.house.gov |date=|accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621055328/http://joebarton.house.gov/Back.aspx?Page=Biography |archivedate=2010-06-21 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n====1984\u201386====\nBarton made his first run for elected office in 1984, when he entered the Republican primary for [[Texas's 6th congressional district]] after three-term incumbent [[Phil Gramm]] left his seat to run for the [[United States Senate]] that year. He finished first in the five-candidate field with 42%,  and very narrowly defeated Max Hoyt in the runoff with 50%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418501 |title=TX District 6 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 May 05, 1984 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201033/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418501 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418504 |title=TX District 6 \u2013 R Runoff Race \u2013 Jun 02, 1984 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029200844/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=418504 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref> He then defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee and former State Representative [[Dan Kubiak]] 57%\u201343%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=50388 |title=TX District 6 Race \u2013 Nov 05, 1984 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029191010/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=50388 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref> Barton was one of six freshmen Republican U.S. congressmen elected from Texas in 1984, known as the [[Texas Six Pack]].<ref>[https://www.dailykos.com/stories/2016/10/30/1588611/-A-legacy-40-years-in-the-making-Comparing-the-candidates-in-the-Texas-6th-TX-06 \"A legacy 40 years in the making: Comparing the candidates in the Texas 6th (TX-06)\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Barton won re-election against Democratic candidate [[Pete Geren]], who was later elected to Congress from a neighboring district. Barton defeated Geren 56%\u201344%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=38378 |title=TX District 6 Race \u2013 Nov 4, 1986 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030010515/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=38378 |archivedate=2013-10-30 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====1988\u20132010====\nDuring this period, Barton won each re-election with 60% of the vote or more.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1738 |title=Candidate \u2013 Joe L. Barton |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030012129/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1738 |archivedate=2013-10-30 |deadurl=no}}</ref> His worst general election performance was in 2006, when he defeated Democratic candidate David Harris 60%\u201337%, a 23-point margin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207706 |title=TX \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204032209/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=207706 |archivedate=2014-02-04 |deadurl=no}}</ref> The 2008 election was his second-worst performance, defeating Democratic candidate Ludwig Otto by a 26-point margin, 62%\u201336%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=401674 |title=TX \u2013 District 06 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022201631/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=401674 |archivedate=2012-10-22 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\nHe was only challenged in the primary twice in this time period: in 1992 and 1994. In 1992, he defeated Mike McGinn 79 to 21%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=558402 |title=TX District 06- R Primary Race \u2013 Mar 10, 1992 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505140248/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=558402 |archivedate=2014-05-05 |deadurl=no}}</ref> In 1994, he defeated Jerry Goode 89%\u201311%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560498 |title=TX District 06- R Primary Race \u2013 Mar 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505140246/http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=560498 |archivedate=2014-05-05 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\nBecause of increasing controversy surrounding his record in office, election battles became  increasingly contentious. In 2011, a [[Political Action Committee|Super PAC]] was formed by Texas conservative groups to remove him and several other long-time incumbents from office.<ref>Slater, Wayne (2012-04-02) [http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/archives/2012/04/texas-super-pac-targets-long-t.html \"Texas super PAC targets long-time GOP incumbents Joe Barton and Ralph Hall\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606164459/http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2012/04/texas-super-pac-targets-long-t.html |date=2012-06-06 }}. ''Dallas Morning News''. <!--accessed 2012-05-01--> <!-- https://web.archive.org/web/20120606164459/http://trailblazersblog.dallasnews.com/2012/04/texas-super-pac-targets-long-t.html --></ref>\nThe [[Democratic National Committee]] used Barton's comments in political ads, shown nationally against all Republican candidates.<ref>Yellin, Jessica (2011-06-18) {{YouTube|9it4s893yDI|\"CNN Debuts DNC ad 'Stop Apologizing'\"}}. ''CNN''. <!--accessed 2012-05-01--></ref> Several websites were created and dedicated to simply removing Barton from office. DefeatJoeBarton.com/ was created by Democratic challengers.  All content was later removed, though the site is still owned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defeatjoebarton.com/ |title=www.defeatjoebarton.com |accessdate=2017-04-23 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504172046/http://www.defeatjoebarton.com/ |archivedate=May 4, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nBarton drew three primary challengers: Joe Chow, Mayor of [[Addison, Texas|Addison]]; Itamar Gelbman, a security consultant; and Frank C. Kuchar, a Dallas businessman and former preacher. Chow is Texas' first [[Asian-American]] mayor. He called Barton \"the most corrupt congressman in the State of Texas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2012/05/rep-joe-barton-on-gop-primary-race-my-real-opponent-is-me/ |title=Rep. Joe Barton on GOP primary race: 'My real opponent is me' &#124; Texas on the Potomac |publisher=[[Houston Chronicle|Houston Chronicle Blogs]] |date=2012-05-17 |author=Dunham, Richard |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522072056/http://blog.chron.com/txpotomac/2012/05/rep-joe-barton-on-gop-primary-race-my-real-opponent-is-me/ |archivedate=2012-05-22 |deadurl=no}}</ref> At the end of March 2012, Barton had $1.3 million in cash on hand, compared with $28,800 for Chow, $178,000 for Gelbman, and $463 for Kuchar.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vaughn |first=Chris |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/2012/05/13/3957102/longtime-us-house-rep-joe-barton.html#storylink=cpy |title=Longtime U.S. House Rep. Joe Barton draws GOP challengers in District 6 race |publisher=Star-telegram.com |date=2012-05-13 |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120713133708/http://www.star-telegram.com/2012/05/13/3957102/longtime-us-house-rep-joe-barton.html |archivedate=2012-07-13 |deadurl=yes}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n\nIn the Republican primary on March 4, Barton won re-nomination to a 16th term in the U.S. House. He polled 32,579 (72.7%); his 2012 primary opponent, Frank Kuchar, trailed with 12,260 votes (27.3%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_race3.htm|title=Republican primary election returns, March 4, 2014|publisher=enr.sos.state.tx.us|accessdate=2014-03-05 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306070205/https://team1.sos.state.tx.us/enr/results/mar04_169_race3.htm |archivedate=2014-03-06 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> On November 4, Barton handily won re-election over Democratic opponent David Cozad.\n\n====2016====\n\nBarton polled 55,197 votes (68.7%) in a three-candidate field for the Republican House nomination in the March 1 primary election. The runner-up, Steven Fowler, received 17,927 votes (22.3%).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_273_state.htm?x=0&y=1414&id=664|title=Republican primary returns|date=March 1, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=March 4, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306143740/https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_273_state.htm?x=0&y=1414&id=664|archivedate=March 6, 2016|df=}}</ref> To win his 17th consecutive term in the House, Barton then defeated in the November 8 general election the Democrat Ruby Faye Woolridge (born 1948) of [[Arlington, Texas|Arlington]], who had polled 22,954 votes (69.7%) in her earlier three-candidate Democratic primary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_233.htm|title=Democratic primary returns|date=March 1, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=March 4, 2016|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306144035/https://enrpages.sos.state.tx.us/public/mar01_233.htm|archivedate=March 6, 2016|df=}}</ref> Barton finished with 159,444 votes (58.3%) to Woolridge's 106,667 (39%); the most any Democrat had received against Barton in his three-decade career.<ref name=autogenerated11>[http://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article186091598.html \"What could happen to Texas Rep. Joe Barton's Congressional seat?\" | The Kansas City Star<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The remaining 7,185 votes (2.6%) went to the [[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] candidate, Darrel Smith, Jr.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist319_state.htm|title=Election Results|date=November 8, 2016|publisher=Texas Secretary of State|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2018====\nTexas's filing deadline for the House seat currently held by Barton is December 11, 2017.<ref name=autogenerated11 /> The primary will be held March 6, 2018.<ref name=autogenerated11 /> Barton initially said that he would run for reelection, but announced on November 30, 2017, that he would not seek reelection in 2018.<ref name=autogenerated19>[https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2017/11/30/rep-joe-barton-will-seek-re-election \"Rep. Joe Barton: I will not seek re-election\",<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Dallas News''.</ref><ref name=autogenerated20>[http://www.cnn.com/2017/11/30/politics/joe-barton-re-election/index.html \"Joe Barton will not seek re-election following nude photo incident\" \u2013 CNNPolitics<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIf Barton resigns from his seat (as predicted by Austin Republican strategist Matt Mackowiak), there will be a special, open primary election in 2018, in which candidates from all parties will appear on a single ballot; if no candidate receives more than 50% of the vote, then the top two vote-getters (regardless of party) will advance to a runoff.<ref name=autogenerated11 /><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2017/11/26/voters-question-whether-congressman-whose-nude-photo-leaked-online-could-win-seat/ \"Voters question whether congressman whose nude photo leaked online could win seat\" \u2013 ''The Washington Post''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDemocrat former educator Ruby Faye Woolridge has indicated she will run for the seat, as have Democrats Jana Lynne Sanchez (endorsed by the [[New Democrat Coalition]] and the environmental group [[Climate Hawks Vote]]), party activist Justin Snider, Levii R. Shocklee of Arlington, and lawyer John Duncan.<ref>[http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article186767093.html \"Texas Rep. Joe Barton's seat could give Latina PR professional an opening\" | McClatchy Washington Bureau<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated15 /><ref name=autogenerated14>[http://www.thenewstribune.com/news/politics-government/article186091598.html \"What could happen to Texas Rep. Joe Barton's Congressional seat?\" | The News Tribune<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=autogenerated12>[http://www.star-telegram.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/bud-kennedy/article186538743.html \"Texas' Joe Barton could get re-elected to Congress despite photo,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref><ref name=autogenerated16>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/local/community/fort-worth/article186846098.html \"Many local Republicans think Joe Barton shouldn't run for re-election,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref> Republicans Jake Ellzey (a retired U.S. Navy fighter pilot and commissioner on the Texas Veterans Commission) and Dr. Monte Mark Mitchell (a Fort Worth physician, attorney, and custom home builder) filed to oppose Barton, and other Republican candidates for Barton's seat may include State Representative [[Tony Tinderholt]], State Senators [[Brian Birdwell]] and [[Konni Burton]], [[Ellis County, Texas|Ellis County]] Commissioner Paul Perry, and former [[Tarrant County]] Tax Assessor-Collector Ron Wright (Barton's former chief of staff and district director).<ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/bud-kennedy/article187706273.html \"Who'll replace Joe Barton? Tax official, ex-fighter in race as Republicans,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref><ref name=autogenerated14 /><ref name=autogenerated7 /><ref name=autogenerated12 /><ref name=autogenerated17>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/politics/New-Calls-from-Within-GOP-for-Rep-Joe-Barton-to-Not-Run-for-Re-Election-460605883.html \"New Calls from Within GOP for Rep. Joe Barton to Not Run for Re-Election\" \u2013 NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.newsmax.com/JohnGizzi/joe-barton-scandal-nude-photo/2017/11/26/id/828142/ \"Scandal Having Impact on Rep. Joe Barton's District\"]</ref><ref name=autogenerated16 /><ref>[https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2017/11/28/rep-joe-barton-faces-new-primary-challenger-sexting-revelation \"Rep. Joe Barton faces new primary challenger after sexting revelation,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Dallas News''.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'' urged that Barton not seek re-election.<ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/opinion/editorials/article186757213.html \"Joe Barton should leave Congress after sending nude photos,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref> Tim O'Hare, the Chairman of the Tarrant County Republican Party, called on Barton \"to not seek re-election and to retire from Congress by the end of [2017],\" saying he is guilty of \"sexual immorality.\"<ref name=autogenerated16 /><ref name=autogenerated17 /> Republican State Senators Konni Burton and Brian Birdwell also urged Barton to not seek re-election.<ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article187189338.html \"State Sen. Konni Burton joins Republicans asking U.S. Rep. Joe Barton to step down,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref><ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/state-politics/article187291883.html \"State Sen. Birdwell asks Joe Barton to not seek re-election,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref> Brian Mayes, a Dallas political consultant, said Barton was vulnerable in his upcoming election battle \"if he gets a motivated opponent\", and that he risked getting lumped in \"fairly or unfairly\" with [[List of federal political sex scandals in the United States|sexual misconduct allegations in Congress]].<ref name=autogenerated8>[https://www.dallasnews.com/news/texas-politics/2017/11/23/texas-rep-joe-barton-might-victim-also-politically-vulnerable-strategists-say \"Texas Rep. Joe Barton might be a victim, but he's also politically vulnerable, strategists say,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Dallas News''.</ref> Barton announced on November 30, 2017, that he would not seek reelection.<ref name=autogenerated19 />\n\n===Tenure===\nBarton voted against the [[Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008]] in both of its manifestations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2008/roll671.xml |title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 671|publisher=Office of the Clerk of the House of Representatives|date=September 29, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2008/roll681.xml |title=Final Vote Results for Roll Call 681|publisher=Office of the Clerk of the House of Representatives|date=October 3, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2011, Barton sponsored the [[U.S. Lighting Energy Policy#Better Use of Light Bulbs Act|Better Use of Light Bulbs Act]], which would repeal the [[Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007]], signed by President [[George W. Bush]]. The 2007 law would set energy efficiency standards for light bulbs, effectively eliminating most or all [[incandescent light bulb]]s. Barton said \"People don't want Congress dictating what [[light fixture]]s they can use.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Caygle, Heather |url=http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Republicans-demand-bulb-law-repeal-1619397.php |title=Republicans demand bulb law repeal |work=[[Houston Chronicle|Houston Chronicle Online]] |location=Washington Bureau |date=2011-03-31 |accessdate=2012-05-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226041645/http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Republicans-demand-bulb-law-repeal-1619397.php |archivedate=2014-02-26 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\nBarton is a member of the [[Freedom Caucus]]<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.texastribune.org/2017/03/26/ted-poe-resigns-freedom-caucus |title= U.S. Rep. Ted Poe resigns from Freedom Caucus |newspaper=Texas Tribune |first=Abby |last=Livingston |date=March 26, 2017 |access-date=February 7, 2018 }}</ref> and the [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> In the first session of the [[115th United States Congress]], Barton was ranked the 42nd most bipartisan member of the [[United States House of Representatives|House]] by the Bipartisan Index, a metric published by [[Richard Lugar#The Lugar Center|The Lugar Center]] and [[Georgetown University|Georgetown's]] [[McCourt School of Public Policy]] to assess [[United States Congress|congressional]] bipartisanship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thelugarcenter.org/assets/htmldocuments/Senate%20Scores%20115th%20Congress%20First%20Session.pdf|publisher=The Lugar Center|title=The Lugar Center - McCourt School Bipartisan Index|date=April 24, 2018|accessdate=July 9, 2018|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n\n;Congressional action\n* Former Chairman of the House Energy and Commerce Committee,<ref name=\"paidwife\">{{cite web  | title= Report says Barton's campaign paid wife |date=2007-06-19|accessdate= 2007-06-20|work=Fort Worth Star-Telegram <!--  removed convenience link http://www.star-telegram.com/national_news/story/141802.html, may be available to buy here http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_multi=ST|&p_text_advanced-0=%28barton%20%22paid%20wife%22%29 -->}}</ref><ref name=\"bbcwarming\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/4693855.stm | title= Politics plays climate 'hockey' |accessdate= 2007-06-20|author=Pease, Roland |publisher=BBC | date=2005-07-18 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307214120/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/4693855.stm |archivedate=2008-03-07 |deadurl=no}}</ref> House sponsor of the [[Energy Policy Act of 2005]],<ref>[https://www.congress.gov/bill/109th-congress/house-bill/6 \"H.R.6 \u2013 109th Congress (2005\u20132006): Energy Policy Act of 2005\" | Congress.gov | Library of Congress<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and chairman of the House\u2013Senate energy conference committee.{{Citation needed|date=June 2007}} On his website he speaks of his diligent work to promote a conservative agenda, and how \"in his first legislative victory as Chairman, the House overwhelmingly passed legislation to limit indecency on the public airwaves.\"<ref>[https://joebarton.house.gov/biography/ \"Biography | U.S. Representative Joe Barton\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n* Both initiated and eliminated \"safe harbor\" provision for [[MTBE]] (in Energy Policy Act of 2005).<ref name=\"MSNBCNews\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2005/POLITICS/04/21/energy.bill.mtbe.ap/ |title=House approves energy bill |date=2005-04-21 |work=CNN |agency=Associated Press |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050424041210/http://www.cnn.com/2005/POLITICS/04/21/energy.bill.mtbe.ap/index.html |archivedate=2005-04-24 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>\n* Co-founded the Congressional Privacy Caucus, cosponsor of the anti-spyware [[Cyber-security regulation#Proposed regulation|SPY ACT]], initiated [[s:National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006|National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006]].\n* Opposed the extension of the [[Voting Rights Act]] in 2006\n* Barton was a leading voice in Congress for forcing [[Digital television transition in the United States|the switch from analog to digital TV]].<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1413451/barton-pushes-for-analog-shut-off Barton Pushes For Analog Shut Off], ''Billboard'' (April 26, 2005).</ref><ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7562876/ns/technology_and_science-tech_and_gadgets/ Lawmaker to press for digital TV deadline: Broadcasters wary because of low adoption rate], Associated Press (April 19, 2005).</ref> \n* Barton has supported the auctioning off the public airwaves to private companies.<ref>Dow Jones, [http://www.mercurynews.com/2008/02/13/fccs-martin-admits-d-block-spectrum-bid-unlikely/ FCC's Martin admits D-block spectrum bid unlikely], ''Mercury News'' (February 13, 2008).</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/story/2008/04/15/gop-lawmakers-call-for-new-airwave-auction-to-pay-for-national-11.html \"GOP Lawmakers Call for New Airwave Auction to Pay for National 911 Communications\"], Associated Press (April 15, 2008).</ref>\n\n==== Global warming ====\n\nPrompted by a February 2005 ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'' article,<ref>{{cite news|author=Regalado, Antonio  |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB110834031507653590 |title=In Climate Debate, The 'Hockey Stick' Leads to a Face-Off |publisher=Wall Street Journal |date=2005-02-14 |accessdate=2010-06-19}}</ref> Barton launched an investigation that year into two [[climate change]] studies from 1998 and 1999.<ref name=\"bbcwarming\"/> In his letters to the authors of the studies he requested details on the studies and the sources of the authors grant funding.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/07/31/tree-ring-circus/ | title= Tree Ring Circus|accessdate= 2007-06-20|author= Milloy, Steven|publisher= Fox News | date=2005-07-31 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002070434/http://www.foxnews.com/story/2005/07/31/tree-ring-circus/ |archivedate=2013-10-02 |deadurl=no}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' condemned Barton's investigation as a \"[[witch-hunt]]\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/07/22/AR2005072201658.html | title= Hunting Witches|accessdate= 2007-06-20|author= Editorial|work= Washington Post | date=2005-07-23}}</ref> During former [[Vice President]] [[Al Gore]]'s testimony to the [[Energy and Commerce Committee]] in March 2007, Barton asserted to Gore that \"You're not just off a little, you're totally wrong\" (climate scientists have refuted Barton's assertion<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.realclimate.org/index.php/archives/2007/04/the-lag-between-temp-and-co2/\n|title=The lag between temperature and CO2. (Gore's got it right.)\n|date=2007-04-27 |accessdate=2014-06-18}}</ref>), stating that \"[[Global warming]] science is uneven and evolving.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/03/21/AR2007032100945.html |author=Pickler, Nedra |title=Gore Implores Congress to Save Planet |work= Washington Post |date=2007-03-21 |accessdate=2014-05-06}}</ref>\n\nUpset with House Speaker Nancy Pelosi's passage of global warming legislation in 2009, he said: \"You can't regulate God.\"<ref name=autogenerated13>[http://content.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1997963,00.html \"Eight More Deep Thoughts from Congressman Joe Barton,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''TIME'', June 18, 2010.</ref> At the same time, Barton implied in 2009 that wind is a \"finite resource,\" and there was a claim made that Barton was suggesting that greater use of wind turbines would \"slow the winds down,\" which would \"cause the temperature to go up,\"<ref name=autogenerated13 /><ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=128117364 \"Opening Panel Round,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] NPR, June 26, 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2009/apr/23/oil-joe-barton \"Leo Hickman: Climate sceptic 'baffles' US energy secretary Steven Chu\" | Environment,<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''The Guardian'', April 23, 2009.</ref> although a report in ''Snopes'' suggested that Barton was merely quoting an academic study which suggested that increased use of wind turbines might have unintended consequences for the environment, and that the claim about the linkage between increased use of wind turbines and slowing down the winds was incorrect.<ref name=twsSnopes111>Snopes, [https://www.snopes.com/politics/soapbox/bartonwind.asp Did Rep. Joe Barton Proclaim 'Wind Is a Finite Resource'? Texas Rep. Joe Barton supposedly once said that 'wind is a finite resource and harnessing it would slow the winds down, which would cause the temperature to go up.'], Retrieved December 16, 2017, \"...he was quoting from a paper written by an academic that questioned whether increased use of wind turbines might have unintended environmental consequences...\"</ref> In 2013, when discussing the Keystone XL pipeline, he referred to the [[Genesis flood narrative]] in the Bible to argue that current climate change isn't man-made.<ref name=huffington_post_10_apr_2013>{{cite news|last=Klene|first=Chelsea|title=Joe Barton Cites Great Flood To Disprove Human Role In Climate Change|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/10/joe-barton-great-flood_n_3055909.html|accessdate=2013-04-13|newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]|date=2013-04-10 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130414024511/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/10/joe-barton-great-flood_n_3055909.html |archivedate=2013-04-14 |deadurl=no}}</ref> Barton rejects the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]] that climate change is real and that human activity is the primary cause.<ref name=\"huffington_post_10_apr_2013\" /><ref name=vice>{{cite news |title=A Guide To The Climate Change Deniers In Congress |at=Texas' Climate Change Deniers |date=April 25, 2017 |accessdate=August 30, 2017 |url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/vvazdx/texas-climate-change-deniers |publisher=[[Vice Media]] |department=Motherboard}}</ref><ref name=buzzfeed20130410>{{cite news |title=Republican Congressman Cites Biblical Great Flood To Say Climate Change Isn't Man-Made |date=April 10, 2013 |first=Andrew |last=Kaczynski |accessdate=September 3, 2017 |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/andrewkaczynski/republican-congressman-cites-biblical-great-flood-to-say-cim |agency=[[BuzzFeed]] |quote=\"I don't think it's a secret that I'm a proponent and supporter of the Keystone pipeline,\" Barton said...\"I would point out that people like me who support hydrocarbon development don't deny that climate is changing,\" he added. \"I think you can have an honest difference of opinion of what's causing that change without automatically being either all in that's all because of mankind or it's all just natural. I think there's a divergence of evidence...If you believe in the Bible, one would have to say the Great Flood is an example of climate change. That certainly wasn't because man had overdeveloped hydrocarbon energy.\"}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=time20100618>{{cite news |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |title=Eight More Deep Thoughts from Rep. Joe Barton |url=http://content.time.com/time/politics/article/0,8599,1997963-1,00.html |first1=Jay |last1=Newton-Small |first2=Katy |last2=Steinmetz |date=June 18, 2010 |accessdate=September 4, 2017 |quote=Barton is a long-time denier of global warming. He's called it \"a triumph over good sense and science\" and in 2007 hearings he told Al Goe, \"You're not just off a little. You're totally wrong.\"}}</ref>\nBarton has \"mocked human-caused climate change\" according to ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/03/us/politics/republican-leaders-climate-change.html |title=How G.O.P. Leaders Came to View Climate Change as Fake Science |last=Davenport |first=Coral |date=June 3, 2017 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2017-06-03 |last2=Lipton |first2=Eric |issn=0362-4331 |quote=Representative Fred Upton, a Michigan Republican who once called climate change \"a serious problem\" and co-sponsored a bill to promote energy-efficient light bulbs, tacked right after the 2010 elections as he battled to be chairman of the powerful House Energy and Commerce Committee against Joe Barton, a Texan who mocked human-caused climate change.}}</ref> and is \"a long-time denier of global warming\" according to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine,<ref name=time20100618/> and \"a longtime skeptic of human involvement in climate change\" according to ''[[HuffPost]]''.<ref name=\"huffington_post_10_apr_2013\"/> In any event, he  suggested that humans will \"adapt\" to climate change because we can \"get shade.\"<ref>[https://washingtonmonthly.com/2009/09/18/joe-barton-environmental-visionary/]</ref> \"Barton has made a reputation for his outspoken rejection of man-made climate change, and for his support for the oil industry,\" according to [[Suzanne Goldenberg]] in ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=US congressman cites biblical flood to dispute human link to climate change |authorlink=Suzanne Goldenberg |first=Suzanne |last=Goldenberg |date=April 10, 2013 |accessdate=September 5, 2017 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/blog/2013/apr/11/republican-biblical-flood-climate-change |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n====Autism bills controversy====\nBarton tried to block the bipartisan [[Combating Autism Act|Combating Autism Act of 2006]]. He said that the money steered toward environmental causes of [[autism]] was not the reason he blocked passage of the bill.<ref>{{cite news |date=2006-10-28 |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/DN-barton_28nat.ART.North.Edition1.3e00d4c.html |title=Activists Putting Heat on Barton |work=Dallas Morning News |author1=Reddy, Sudeep |author2=Loftis, Randy Lee|accessdate=2009-12-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101020043618/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/dn/latestnews/stories/DN-barton_28nat.ART.North.Edition1.3e00d4c.html |archivedate=2010-10-20 |deadurl=yes}}</ref>\n\nThe controversy stemmed from the conflict between two bills in the House and Senate.  Barton introduced the National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://olpa.od.nih.gov/legislation/109/publiclaws/reformact06.asp |title=National Institutes of Health Reform Act of 2006 |publisher=[[Office of Legislative Policy and Analysis]] |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501004808/http://olpa.od.nih.gov/legislation/109/publiclaws/reformact06.asp |archivedate=2013-05-01 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> while Senator [[Rick Santorum]] introduced the Autism bill.  Santorum said in a CNN interview that the Senate bill was intended to be \"fit into\" Barton's bill in the House bill. He stated that \"I was in constant conversation with him [Barton] and many House members all last week in an attempt to help the NIH bill come through the Senate, as well as try to move the Combating Autism bill through the Senate.\"  Santorum stated that the Senate bill would investigate possible environmental causes, while the House bill would prevent that.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cLdXcb5Pc6Q&feature=watch_response |title=CNN Combating Autism Act Joe Barton |publisher=YouTube |date=2006-10-05 |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref>\n\nBarton let the bill die in committee, which upset many people who were vocal about saying Barton had sacrificed the interests of autistic children in the interests of the oil and gas companies that donate heavily to his campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aa2-bFlASpo&feature=related |title=Joe Barton Autism Parent Meeting \u2013 TURNED AWAY BY POLICE!|publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00005656 |title=Joe Barton: Campaign Finance/Money \u2013 Summary \u2013 Representative 2014 |publisher=OpenSecrets |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029195541/http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00005656 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====BP oil spill controversy====\nIn June 2010, Barton accused the Obama administration of a \"$20 billion [[Extortion|shakedown]]\" of oil giant [[BP]] after the company reached an agreement with the administration to establish an [[escrow]] account to pay the claims of people harmed by the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill|''Deepwater Horizon'' oil spill]] in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vvKZh3EY9S4&feature=player_embedded |title=Barton- 'I Apologize' To BP For Escrow Fund |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2010-06-19}}</ref> He made the accusation at the outset of a House hearing where BP's chief executive officer, [[Tony Hayward]], appeared for the first time before Congress.  Facing Hayward at the witness table, Barton said, \"I apologize. I do not want to live in a country where any time a citizen or a corporation does something that is legitimately wrong, is subject to some sort of political pressure that is, again, in my words \u2014 amounts to a shakedown, so I apologize.\"<ref name=\"barton-bp-apology-cbs\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-apologizes-to-bps-tony-hayward-for-white-house-shakedown-video/ |title=Rep. Joe Barton Apologizes to BP's Tony Hayward for White House \"Shakedown\" |author=Montopoli, Brian |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2010-06-18|publisher= CBS News |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131204145144/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-apologizes-to-bps-tony-hayward-for-white-house-shakedown-video/|archivedate=2013-12-04 |deadurl=no}}</ref> Prior to the establishment of the agreement, the Obama administration had been public in their criticism of BP for the oil spill.<ref name=\"barton-bp-apology-cbs\"/>\n\nBarton's remarks were criticized by White House spokesman [[Robert Gibbs]] and Vice President [[Joe Biden]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/06/17/us-oil-spill-apology-idUSTRE65G42D20100617 |title=Apology to BP's Hayward triggers uproar |agency=Reuters |author=Holland, Steve |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216170009/https://www.reuters.com/article/2010/06/17/us-oil-spill-apology-idUSTRE65G42D20100617 |archivedate=2013-02-16 |deadurl=no}}</ref> GOP congressional leadership<ref>{{cite news|title=GOP rushes to clean up Joe Barton mess |author=Allen, Jonathan |author2=Sherman, Jake |publisher=[[The Politico]] |date=2010-06-17 |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/38700.html |archivedate=May 6, 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PNQk3mHj?url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/38700.html |df= }}</ref> as well as by Barton's fellow Republicans, some of whom called on him to relinquish his leadership role in the [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|House Energy Subcomittee]].<ref>Collette, Christopher (2010-06-18) [https://archive.is/20130210012507/http://www.wtsp.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=134419 \"Florida Congressmen denounce Joe Barton's apology to BP\"]. [[Associated Press]] via [[WTSP]].<!-- https://web.archive.org/web/20140506213703/http://archive.wtsp.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=134419 --></ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jo Bonner piles on Joe Barton |author=Allen, Jonathan |publisher=[[The Politico]] |date=2010-06-18 |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/38736.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6PNRPdKXn?url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/38736.html |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>\n\nBarton later said that his earlier remarks had been \"misconstrued\" and that he believed BP was responsible for the accident.  Later that day, he issued a statement apologizing for using the term \"shakedown\" and fully retracted his apology to BP.<ref name=\"MSNBCNews\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7574562/ns/politics/t/house-approves-billion-energy-package |title=House approves $12 billion energy bill |publisher=NBC News|date=2005-04-21 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506214954/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/7574562/ns/politics/t/house-approves-billion-energy-package |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-retracts-apology-to-bps-tony-hayward/|title=Rep. Joe Barton Retracts Apology to BP's Tony Hayward |author=Montopoli, Brian |date=2010-06-17 |accessdate=2014-05-06|publisher= CBS News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506210451/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-joe-barton-retracts-apology-to-bps-tony-hayward/ |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n====Sodomy and abortion====\nIn 2010, Barton backed a policy platform that called for re-criminalizing [[sodomy]] in Texas.<ref name=autogenerated9>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/joe-barton-revenge-porn_us_5a171883e4b0d4906caddd94 Rep. Joe Barton\u2019s Explicit Photo Leak Could Be Revenge Porn | HuffPost<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  He has 100% ratings from socially conservative groups such as the [[Family Research Council]] and the [[Christian Coalition of America]] for his opposition to [[abortion]] and [[LGBTQ]] rights.<ref name=autogenerated9 /><ref>[http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-joe-barton-nude-photo-20171122-story.html \"Congressman told woman he would report her to Capitol Police if she exposed his secret sex life\" \u2013 ''Chicago Tribune''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.star-telegram.com/news/local/community/fort-worth/article29207584.html \"Fort Worth protesters demand funding cuts for Planned Parenthood,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref>\n\n====CREW report====\nThe organization [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] (CREW) put Barton on its \"CREW's Most Corrupt Report 2011\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/joe-barton |title=Joe Barton (R-TX) &#124; CREW's Most Corrupt Members of Congress |publisher=Crewsmostcorrupt.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029190726/http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/joe-barton |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/most-corrupt-report-2011 |title=CREW\u2019s Most Corrupt Report 2011 &#124; CREW's Most Corrupt Members of Congress |publisher=Crewsmostcorrupt.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029193151/http://www.crewsmostcorrupt.org/mostcorrupt/entry/most-corrupt-report-2011 |archivedate=2013-10-29 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> The article stated that on Barton's 2008 financial disclosure statement, he inaccurately reported on the source of a natural gas interest that he bought into.  The share was purchased through a longtime donor and supporter, who later died. This was discovered by the ''[[Dallas Morning News]]'' in 2010.<ref name=\"dallasnews1\">Michaels, Dave (2010-02-03) [http://www.dallasnews.com/news/washington/20100203-U-S-Rep-Joe-6388.ece \"U.S. Rep. Joe Barton's gas well stake raises ethical questions\"]. ''Dallas Morning News''. <!--accessed 2012-04-30--><!-- https://web.archive.org/web/20120412091049/http://www.dallasnews.com/news/washington/20100203-U-S-Rep-Joe-6388.ece --></ref> According to the ''Dallas Morning News'' article, Barton made over $100,000 on the investment.  The article and CREW Report both pointed out how Barton buying this undervalued asset from an \"advisor\" on energy issues could be a conflict of interest to the Congressman's position as the Chair of the House's Energy Subcommittee.  It quoted [[James A. Thurber|James Thurber]], a Distinguished Professor of Government at [[American University]], as saying: \"If you are elected as a public servant to try to do what is right for the public generally and then you use that position to help bring in material wealth, I think it's unethical.\"<ref name=\"dallasnews1\"/>\n\nCREW also reported that Barton paid his wife Terri $57,759 in salary and bonuses, from his campaign funds in the 2006 election cycle.<ref name=\"ethicsreport\">{{cite web |url=http://www.citizensforethics.org/page/-/PDFs/Reports/Family%20Affair%20%28House%29%20-%20Full%20Report.pdf?nocdn=1 |title=Family Affair \u2013 Full Report |accessdate=2014-05-06 |publisher=Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506224317/http://www.citizensforethics.org/page/-/PDFs/Reports/Family%20Affair%20%28House%29%20-%20Full%20Report.pdf?nocdn=1 |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> A spokesman said that Terri served as the campaign's outreach director and planned fund raising and special events.<ref name=\"paidwife\"/> in addition, Barton's daughter Kristin was paid $12,622 in salary and bonuses, and his mother, Nell Barton, was paid $7,000 for a car.<ref name=\"paidwife\"/>\n\n====Crude oil ban====\nBarton expressed in September 2014 his full support of the U.S. lifting the [[Energy Policy and Conservation Act#Crude oil export ban, 1977-2015|40-year-old ban]] on [[crude oil]] exports \u2013 an issue that sparked controversy among members of the Republican Party. Several research reports had found that exporting the glut of shale oil would ultimately lower U.S. and global fuel prices, rather than raise them; U.S. public opinion was divided on the issue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Volcovici|first1=Valerie|title=Texas lawmaker Barton backs lifting oil export ban despite peers' misgivings|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/01/us-oil-exports-usa-lawmaker-idUSKBN0GW31R20140901|website=Reuters|accessdate=September 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Online poker====\nBarton has sought to permit [[online poker]], and regulate it on a federal level.<ref name=autogenerated10>[https://www.pokernews.com/news/2015/06/rep-joe-barton-introduces-a-new-bill-that-would-regulate-onl-22059.htm Rep. Joe Barton Introduces New Bill That Would Regulate Online Poker in the US | PokerNews<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> To that end, he has introduced the Online Poker Act of 2011, the Internet Poker Freedom Act of 2013, and the Internet Poker Freedom Act of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardschat.com/news/joe-barton-of-texas-federal-online-poker-bill-10712|title=US Representative Joe Barton of Texas Pushes In Federal Poker Bill|work=Cardschat|accessdate=2 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated10 />\n\n====Health care====\nBarton favors repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] (ACA, or Obamacare).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/06/gop-cant-win-health-care-king-burwell-obamacare-119290|title=Why the GOP Can't Win on Health Care|work=POLITICO Magazine|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref> Explaining why the [[American Health Care Act]] (the House Republicans' bill to repeal and replace for the Affordable Care Act) failed in March 2017, Barton said, \"Sometimes you're playing fantasy football and sometimes you're in the real game. We knew the president, if we could get a repeal bill to his desk, would almost certainly veto it. This time we knew if it got to the president's desk it would be signed.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/dc/leadership-pulls-obamacare-repeal|title='The Bill Is Over': House GOP Pulls Health Care Bill Before Sure Defeat|work=Talking Points Memo|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://theweek.com/speedreads/688408/republican-congressman-shockingly-honest-about-why-ahca-failed|title=This Republican congressman was shockingly honest about why the AHCA failed|date=2017-03-24|access-date=2017-03-24}}</ref>\n\n====Hurricane Harvey relief====\nBarton voted against [[Hurricane Harvey]] relief in 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/22/magazine/the-voices-in-blue-americas-head.html?smid=tw-nytimes&smtyp=cur|title=The Voices in Blue America's Head|last=Zengerle|first=Jason|access-date=2017-11-22|language=en}}</ref> Barton said that he could not support an increase in the [[United States debt ceiling|debt ceiling]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n====Immigration====\nBarton supported President [[Donald Trump]]'s 2017 [[Executive Order 13769]] banning entry to the United States by nationals of seven Muslim-majority nations.<ref name=\"Blake1\">{{cite web|last1=Blake|first1=Aaron|title=Coffman, Gardner join Republicans against President Trump's travel ban; here's where the rest stand|url=http://www.denverpost.com/2017/01/29/republicans-on-trump-travel-ban/|website=Denver Post|accessdate=January 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Barton called on the House leadership to pass naturalization legislation for children who came across the border illegally with their parents.<ref>Drusch, Andrea. (9 November 2017). \"After three decades in Congress, Rep. Barton keeps changing, keeps surviving\". [http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/national/article183745136.html McClatchy DC website] Retrieved November 15, 2017.</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]] (Chair ''emeritus'')\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade|Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Communications and Technology|Subcommittee on Communications and Technology]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Environment and Economy|Subcommittee on Environment and Economy]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Health|Subcommittee on Health]]\n** [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations|Subcommittee on Oversight and Investigations]]\n\n==1993 U.S. Senate election==\n{{See also|United States Senate special election in Texas, 1993}}\nIn 1993, Barton ran in the special election for the U.S. Senate seat vacated by the resignation of [[Lloyd Bentsen]], who became [[United States Secretary of the Treasury]] in the [[Clinton administration]]. Barton finished third in the contest, behind state treasurer [[Kay Bailey Hutchison]] and Senator [[Bob Krueger]], thus missing a runoff slot. He divided the more conservative vote in that election with House colleague [[Jack Fields]] of [[Houston, Texas|Houston]].\n\n==Barton Family Foundation==\nThe [[Barton Family Foundation]] was established in 2005 to support charities within the congressman's district.  His daughter-in-law, Amy Barton, is the Foundation's Executive Director.  Major energy corporations, such as the Chicago-based [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]] producer, [[Exelon]] Corporation, make major gifts to the Foundation. In June 2008, at a time when Barton had introduced legislation to assist corporations with the recycling of spent nuclear fuel, the corporation donated $25,000 to the Foundation. Exelon has also donated $80,000 to Barton's campaign funds. The Foundation gave $90,000 to the local [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys and Girls Club]], this is the only recorded donation made by the Foundation in its seven-year history.<ref name=Sepee>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/apr/06/congressmans-foundation-not-so-charitable/?page=all |title=Congressman's foundation not so charitable; Barton's group gives less than 25% to public causes|first=Jerry |last=Seper|work=Washington Times |date=2009-04-06 |page=A.1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506222434/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/apr/06/congressmans-foundation-not-so-charitable/?page=all |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n==Sex scandal==\n\nIn November 2017, nude [[selfie]] pictures of Barton surfaced online, which he acknowledged were authentic, and which he apologized for to his constituents.<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref name=autogenerated4 /> He confirmed he himself took the photo, apparently from a video of him [[masturbating]], and sent it to women with whom he was having consensual sexual relationships.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/texas-congressman-apologizes-nude-online-selfie/story?id=51331252 \"Texas congressman apologizes for nude online selfie\"] [[ABC News]]</ref><ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/veteran-us-congressman-joe-barton-admits-he-sent-naked-selfies-53csmzsxs \"Veteran US Congressman Joe Barton admits he sent naked selfies\" | ''The Times & The Sunday Times''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> An anonymous [[Twitter]] user posted the photo of Barton, who had pointed his camera upward from below his genitals, next to a text message reading, \"I want you soo bad. Right now. Deep and hard.\"<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nAn anonymous woman said that she had received the selfie and other explicit images from Barton, but had not been the person who posted any of them on the internet. She also shared with the ''Washington Post'' a 2015 recorded phone call in which Barton warned her against using the explicit materials \"in a way that would negatively affect my career\", threatening to report her to the [[United States Capitol Police|Capitol Police]] if she did so.<ref>[http://thehill.com/homenews/house/361642-barton-threatened-to-report-woman-to-capitol-police-if-she-shared-sexually \"Barton threatened to report the woman to Capitol Police if she shared sexually explicit photos of him: report\"] Jacqueline Thomsen, [[thehill.com]] 2017-11-22</ref> On the taped phone call, Barton said \"... I ... met you twice while married and had sex with you on two different occasions\"; the woman said that they had slept together in 2012 in Washington, DC, and in 2014 in Texas, and that the Congressman had reimbursed her for her airfare in cash on both occasions.<ref name=autogenerated6 /> The woman also shared with the ''Washington Post'' text and [[social media]] messages Barton exchanged with her, as well as a 53-second cellphone video in which Barton recorded himself masturbating.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/congressman-told-woman-he-would-report-her-to-capitol-police-if-she-exposed-his-secret-sex-life/2017/11/22/e3345862-cf10-11e7-a1a3-0d1e45a6de3d_story.html \"Congressman on tape tells woman he would report her to Capitol Police because she could expose his secret sex life\"] Mike DeBonis and Elise Viebeck, ''[[Washington Post]]'', November 22, 2017</ref> She described to the newspaper encounters and contact with Barton spanning a five-year period, beginning in 2011.<ref name=autogenerated6>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/congressman-told-woman-he-would-report-her-to-capitol-police-if-she-exposed-his-secret-sex-life/2017/11/22/e3345862-cf10-11e7-a1a3-0d1e45a6de3d_story.html \"Rep. Joe Barton told woman he would report her to Capitol Police if she exposed secret sex life\" \u2013 ''The Washington Post''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She said she came forward because: \"It's not normal for a member of Congress who runs on a GOP platform of family values and conservatism to be scouring the Internet looking for a new sexual liaison.\"<ref>[http://www.sltrib.com/news/nation-world/2017/11/23/texas-congressman-told-woman-he-would-report-her-to-capitol-police-if-she-exposed-his-secret-sex-life/ \"Texas congressman told woman he would report her to Capitol Police if she exposed his secret sex life\" \u2013 ''The Salt Lake Tribune''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nA week later a second woman, Kelly Canon, a board member of the Arlington Republican Club and a member of the Republican Women of Arlington who is a constituent of Barton's, shared a series of messages \u2014 some with sexual overtones \u2014 that Barton had sent to her.<ref name=autogenerated18>[http://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article187115778.html \"He talked panties and politics: Woman shares Facebook messages from Texas politician\" | ''Miami Herald''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Barton sent the messages in 2012 and 2013, while Barton was married to his second wife.<ref name=autogenerated18 /> The messages included questions from Barton about whether Canon was \"wearing a tank top only .. and no panties,\" followed by \"answer me miss evasive.\"<ref name=autogenerated18 /> Barton also messaged her that \"men are men...and u r definitely a sexy woman.\" When Canon responded that \"all the good ones are married,\" Barton replied: \"I dont know about good..but I am married ... but ...I am not thinking good thoughts at this moment ... blush.\"<ref name=autogenerated18 /> Barton confirmed that he had the message exchange.<ref name=autogenerated18 />\n\nA third woman, Cheryl Small, said on November 30, 2017, that Barton had sex with her multiple times in his Ennis office while he was married.<ref>[http://www.wbap.com/2017/11/30/chris-krok-joe-barton-exclusive/ \"Chris Krok: Joe Barton Exclusive\" | News Talk WBAP-AM<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHis second ex-wife said: \"Of course I wasn't surprised. I guess I was more surprised that some of these ladies finally came forward.\"<ref name=autogenerated22>[http://www.wfaa.com/news/politics/congressman-joe-bartons-ex-wife-talks-about-multiple-extramarital-affairs/496254105 \"Congressman Joe Barton's ex-wife talks about multiple extramarital affairs\" | WFAA.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She said she found it ironic that Barton was one of President [[Bill Clinton]]'s loudest critics during the [[Monica Lewinsky scandal]].<ref name=autogenerated22 /> Similarly, columnist Jim Schutze of the ''[[Dallas Observer]]'' noted that Barton practically built his political career \"on condemning the behavior of others and even on trying to make other people's private behavior against the law ....\"<ref>[http://www.dallasobserver.com/news/clinton-barton-and-farenthold-the-different-flavors-of-hypocrisy-10134650], ''Dallas Observer''.</ref>\n\nWhile Barton had no plans to resign immediately, according to a spokeswoman,<ref name=autogenerated1 /> and initially had said that he would run for reelection in 2018, a number of state and local politicians indicated that they might challenge him in the 2018 election for his seat.<ref>[https://www.dallasnews.com/news/politics/2017/11/22/ennis-rep-joe-barton-apologizing-sexually-explicit-photo \"Joe Barton apologizes for explicit photo, but he doesn't plan to resign\"] ''[[Dallas News]]''.</ref><ref name=autogenerated20 /> Barton hired a [[crisis communication]] firm, and said he had suffered a \"potential crime.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/22/us/politics/joe-barton-explicit-photo-twitter.html \"Senior Texas Republican Swept Up Into Storm Over Explicit Photo\"] Nicholas Fandos and Jonathan Martin, ''[[The New York Times]]'' Nov. 22, 2017</ref> Outlets including ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', NBC and CNN opined that Barton might be a victim of [[revenge porn]], which\u2014though not a federal crime\u2014is a class A [[misdemeanor]] in Texas, punishable by up to one year in county jail and up to a $4,000 fine.<ref>[http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2017/11/22/congressman_joe_barton_might_have_been_the_victim_of_revenge_porn.html \"Congressman Joe Barton Might Have Been the Victim of Revenge Porn\"], [[Slate.com]], November 22, 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/congress/texas-rep-joe-barton-may-be-victim-revenge-porn-n823676|title=Texas Rep. Joe Barton may be a victim of revenge porn|first=Danny|last=Cevallos|publisher=NBC|date=2017-11-23|accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/11/23/politics/joe-barton-image-revenge-porn/index.html|title=Explicit Barton image raises possibility of 'revenge porn'|first1=MJ|last1=Lee|first2=Juana|last2=Summers|first3=Sunlen|last3=Serfaty|publisher=CNN|date=2017-11-24|accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref>\n\nRandy Bellomy, Chairman of the [[Ellis County, Texas|Ellis County]] Republican Party, said \"His lifestyle is inconsistent with Republican ideals, and he has brought disgrace not only to Ellis County and the 6th Congressional District, but also to the people of Texas and this great nation.\"<ref>[http://www.wfaa.com/news/local/texas-news/republicans-say-barton-brought-disgrace-to-ellis-co-as-new-explicit-messages-arise/495609973 \"Republicans say Barton 'brought disgrace to Ellis Co.' as new explicit messages arise\" | WFAA.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  Brian Mayes, a Dallas political consultant, said that the sexting \"is something you'd expect from a young, immature college kid, not a grandfather.\"<ref name=autogenerated8 /> Texas GOP Chairman James Dickey said that the case is distinguishable from that of former Congressman [[Anthony Weiner]] and [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandals|his sexting scandal]], but that the two controversies share one \"consistent message that everyone should take to heart: We should all think very hard before we post, text or otherwise share anything.\"<ref name=autogenerated8 /> Barton announced on November 30, 2017, that he would not seek reelection.<ref name=autogenerated19 />\n\nThe ''[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]'' ran an editorial in reaction entitled \"Hey Joe Barton, skipping the next election is not enough. It's time to go.\"<ref name=autogenerated21>[http://www.star-telegram.com/opinion/editorials/article187189108.html \"Joe Barton Republican step down United States House of Representatives,\"<!-- Bot generated title -->] ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram''.</ref> It opined that it was not appropriate for Barton \u2013 who \"can no longer be taken seriously\" \u2013 to continue to represent the 6th Congressional District for another year, until January 2019.<ref name=autogenerated21 />\n\n==Personal life==\nBarton was divorced from his first wife (Jeanette/Janet Sue Winslow) in 2003. He remarried in 2004, and divorced from his second wife (Terri) in 2015.<ref name=autogenerated5>[http://files.usgwarchives.net/tx/harrison/vitals/divorces/1992/hariv92.txt Vital Records \u2013 Harrison County, TX \u2013 Divorces 1992]</ref><ref name=autogenerated7 /><ref>Maria Recio, [http://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/national-politics/article79072767.html Long-timer Joe Barton seeks to regain powerful chairmanship in Congress], ''Fort Worth Star-Telegram'' (May 21, 2016).</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>[http://www.newsweek.com/republican-congressman-joe-barton-victim-revenge-porn-720235 Is Republican Congressman Joe Barton A Victim Of Revenge Porn?<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2017 he was again engaged.<ref name=autogenerated7 /> His wife Terri said she filed for divorce after evidence that Barton had engaged in multiple affairs, and finding \"a very sexually explicit video of one of his mistresses.\"\n\nHe has four children and five grandchildren.<ref name=HouseBio/> In December 2005, Barton suffered a heart attack and was taken to [[George Washington University Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/93334-Barton_Has_Heart_Attack.php |title=Barton Has Heart Attack |author=Eggerton, John  |publisher=Broadcastingcable.com |date=2005-12-16 |accessdate=2010-06-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140506222156/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/news/news-articles/barton-has-heart-attack/71135 |archivedate=2014-05-06 |deadurl=no}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{s-start}}\n|+ {{ushr|Texas|6|}}: Results 1984\u20132016<ref name=\"clerk\">{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |title=Office of the House Clerk \u2013 Electoral Statistics |publisher=Clerk of the United States House of Representatives |accessdate= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070725184700/http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |archivedate=July 25, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"fedelect\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/pubrec/electionresults.shtml|title=Election Results|publisher=[[Federal Election Commission]] |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe |title=1992 \u2013 Current ELECTION HISTORY |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Texas]] |accessdate=2013-10-26 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109062336/http://elections.sos.state.tx.us/elchist.exe |archivedate=January 9, 2014 }}</ref>\n! Year\n!\n! Republican\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Democratic\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n! Third Party\n! Party\n! Votes\n! %\n!\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1984|1984]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Joe Barton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |131,482\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |57%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |[[Dan Kubiak]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |100,799\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |43%\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House election, 1986|1986]]\n||\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |'''Joe Barton'''\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |86,190\n|{{party shading/Republican}} |56%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |[[Pete Geren]]\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |68,270\n|{{party shading/Democratic}} |44%\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\